LE MANS, France (AP) — Italian Enea Bastianini overtook countryman Francesco Bagnaia to win the French MotoGP on Sunday, while world champion Fabio Quartararo saw his championship lead cut after finishing fourth behind Spaniard Aleix Espargaro. Bastianini’s third win of the season pushed the Ducati rider closer to Espargaro in the standings, while Espargaro trimmed the Frenchman Quartararo’s lead from seven points to four.“My pace was really nice,” Bastianini said.Australian Jack Miller finished second for Ducati while the Aprilia rider Espargaro just fended off Quartararo’s Yamaha.“It was a super difficult race, one of the most difficult of my career,” Espargaro said. “Every time I got closer to Jack I started to have some troubles (and) I knew Fabio was behind me. But I did it.”The 24-year-old Bastianini overtook Bagnaia seven laps from the end of the race, but Bagnaia overtook straight back. ADVERTISEMENTThen the pressure told on Bastianini’s next attack as Bagnaia went straight ahead on a turn and lost the lead. On the next lap, he was out of the race after crashing. He was pushing too hard and his Ducati toppled to the left, throwing him off.Bagnaia set a new lap record in qualifying Saturday at the Le Mans circuit en route to his second straight pole position after Spain two weeks ago.Auto RacingHerta makes all right moves to win wet, wild IndyCar GPFrom bummer to baby, Kyle Busch heads to Kansas on high notePower's late qualifying run puts him on pole for Indy GPAndretti receives direction on how to proceed with F1 bidMiller, last year’s winner, qualified second and zoomed into first after a great start, but Bagnaia soon reclaimed the lead.Bastianini started from fifth, but with 16 laps left he powered his Ducati past Miller into second. Then he set off after Bagnaia, with Bagnaia’s lead soon reduced to half a second.Quartararo started fourth behind Espargaro and did not look his best on his home track.Alex Rins fell early on after going straight on and sliding off his bike. The Spaniard got back up and continued.Jorge Martin came off his bike with 10 laps to go. He was unharmed but his Ducati briefly caught fire as it lay on its side.___More AP auto racing: https://apnews.com/hub/auto-racing and https://twitter.com/AP_Sports